<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What size generator do I need for my house?", answer: "Add up the running watts of everything you want to power, then add the highest single motor starting surge. For essentials only (fridge, lights, sump pump, furnace blower) you typically need a 3,500-5,000 watt generator. For whole-house with central AC you need 10,000-15,000 watts. For whole-house with a heat pump and electric water heater you need 20,000-25,000 watts. Add 20% headroom for safety and future loads." },
  { question: "What is the difference between running and starting watts?", answer: "Running (rated) watts is the steady power an appliance draws while operating normally. Starting (surge) watts is the brief in-rush current that induction motors draw for the first second or two to overcome inertia — typically 2-3× the running wattage. Resistive loads (lights, heaters, range elements) have no surge; motors (fridges, well pumps, AC compressors) have large surges. A generator must handle the biggest single motor starting without stalling." },
  { question: "Do I add all the motor starting surges together?", answer: "No — only count the largest single motor surge. Motors don't all start simultaneously, so the generator only needs to handle the biggest inrush plus everything else running steady state. This calculator uses that approach automatically: total running watts + the biggest single (starting − running) delta." },
  { question: "What size generator runs a well pump and fridge?", answer: "Running watts: 1,200 pump + 700 fridge + 200 lights + 500 small loads = 2,600 W. The well pump has the biggest starting surge (3,600 − 1,200 = 2,400 W delta). Peak = 2,600 + 2,400 = 5,000 W. Add 20% headroom = 6,000 W generator minimum. A 7,500-watt portable is the typical practical choice." },
  { question: "Do I need a transfer switch?", answer: "To legally power permanently wired appliances (furnace, well pump, HVAC) you need a manual or automatic transfer switch to disconnect from the utility. Backfeeding through a dryer outlet is dangerous and illegal — it can electrocute lineworkers. A simple 6-10 circuit manual transfer switch costs about $300 plus installation and is required by code." }
]) %>

